	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64120845"><p>My state charges ME sales tax on stuff that I buy from out-of-state using the Internet.  This taxation existed prior to the Internet, is practiced by many states, and is a tax states impose on <i>their own residents.</i></p><p>California is doing the exact opposite.  It is charging the out-of-state vendor income tax on what they sell to California residents.</p><p>That is what seems like overreach to me.  If the person does not live in your state, then they are not in your tax jurisdiction.  Or rather, that is how it seems to me that things should be.  It turns out, things are not this way.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64120845">
